<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-907-366  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 907 366.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  Nov 27 1989 pB7B(W) pB7B(E) 16 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Palm-top computers get thumbs down, shunned by people as costly,confusing.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Manges, Michele.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Pocket or 'palm-top' computers are not selling as well in the USas they have in Japan, where they were originally marketed.andP;  The'palm-top' computers often cost $250 and up, and are accompaniedby instruction manuals that can run up to 212 pages.andP;  Theelectronic organizers contain four-line to eight-line screens andcan store addresses, appointments, a calculator and a world clock.andO;Corporations such as Casio Computer Ltd and Sharp Corp are quickto introduce add-on devices to their electronic organizers thatcan perform language translation and allow exchange of informationwith microcomputers.andP;  With each add-on device, the price of apersonal organizer increases, until the price tag is similar tothat of a notebook computer, which is easier to use and moreversatile.andP;  Fewer than one percent of US consumers surveyed saidthat they would buy a pocket computer.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     New ProductHand-held computersMarket Entry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>